## The full picture (what "logging & observability" means on OCP)

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                     Cluster Logging Operator (CLO)                │
│                                                                     │
│  ClusterLogForwarder (CR)  ──defines pipelines──►  where logs go   │
│         ▲                                                          │
│         │ reads from                                               │
│  Collector DaemonSet (Vector, one pod per node)                    │
│         │ tails                                                    │
│  /var/log/containers/*, /var/log/audit/*, journald                 │
│                                                                     │
└──────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┘
                                │ forwards to
                                ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                          Loki Operator                              │
│                                                                     │
│  LokiStack (CR) ─── size, storage, tenants, retention               │
│         │                                                           │
│    ┌────┴─────┬──────────┬───────────┬─────────────┬───────────┐  │
│ distributor  ingester   querier   query-frontend  compactor  gateway│
│                                                                     │
│         │ writes chunks/index to                                    │
│         ▼                                                           │
│  Object storage (ODF/Noobaa, S3, Azure Blob, GCS, Swift...)          │
└──────────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────────────────┘
                                │
                                ▼
              OpenShift Console "Logging" plugin  (or your Grafana)
```

Separately, but often confused with "logging," there's the **metrics** side (Cluster Monitoring Operator → Prometheus/Thanos/Alertmanager) — I'll include a quick check for that too since real observability is both, and Loki can even alert via its own Ruler component wired to Alertmanager.

Now the commands. Run these as your cluster-admin (or a role with sufficient view access) and share the output — I'll interpret each block.

---

### Phase 1 — What's actually installed

```bash
# Which logging/observability operators are subscribed
oc get subscriptions -A | grep -iE "logging|loki|elasticsearch|tempo"

# Their current install state and version
oc get csv -A | grep -iE "logging|loki|elasticsearch"

# The core CRs that define your setup
oc get clusterlogforwarder -A
oc get lokistack -A
oc get clusterlogging -A          # legacy CR, may or may not exist depending on your CLO version
```

This tells us: which operator generation you're on (5.x legacy `ClusterLogging`-driven model vs 6.x `ClusterLogForwarder`-only model), and whether you're on Loki (modern) or still have Elasticsearch remnants.

---

### Phase 2 — LokiStack detail (the Loki cluster itself)

```bash
oc get lokistack <name> -n openshift-logging -o yaml
```

Specifically check inside that output for:
- `spec.size` — e.g. `1x.demo`, `1x.extra-small`, `1x.small`, `1x.medium` (drives replica counts of each Loki component)
- `spec.storage` — which object storage secret it's using
- `spec.limits` — retention/ingestion limits per tenant
- `status.componentStatus` — health of distributor/ingester/querier/compactor/gateway/indexGateway

```bash
# All the actual Loki component pods
oc get pods -n openshift-logging -l app.kubernetes.io/instance=<lokistack-name>

# Quick health check across them
oc get pods -n openshift-logging -o wide | grep -iE "distributor|ingester|querier|compactor|gateway"
```

---

### Phase 3 — The collector (how logs get from pods into Loki)

```bash
oc get clusterlogforwarder instance -n openshift-logging -o yaml
```
This CR is the actual routing table — it defines **inputs** (application/infrastructure/audit), **outputs** (your lokistack, and possibly external syslog/Kafka/HTTP if you forward anywhere else), and **pipelines** connecting them.

```bash
# Collector daemonset — should have one pod per node
oc get ds -n openshift-logging
oc get pods -n openshift-logging -l component=collector -o wide

# Spot-check a collector pod's own logs for forwarding errors
oc logs -n openshift-logging <collector-pod-name> --tail=100
```

---

### Phase 4 — Storage backend

```bash
# Which secret LokiStack references for object storage
oc get lokistack <name> -n openshift-logging -o jsonpath='{.spec.storage.secret.name}'

# Inspect that secret's keys (not values) to see provider type
oc get secret <secret-name> -n openshift-logging -o jsonpath='{.data}' | tr ',' '\n'

# If using OpenShift Data Foundation / Noobaa as the S3-compatible backend
oc get objectbucketclaim -A
```

In an air-gapped environment this is usually ODF/Noobaa or an internal S3-compatible endpoint rather than public cloud storage — worth confirming since that also affects your retention/compaction sizing.

---

### Phase 5 — Visualization

```bash
# Console logging plugin (built-in UI under Observe > Logs)
oc get consoleplugin | grep -i logging
oc get pods -n openshift-logging -l app.kubernetes.io/component=lokistack-gateway

# If you're also running your own Grafana (separate from the built-in console plugin)
oc get pods -A -l app.kubernetes.io/name=grafana
oc get route -A | grep -i grafana
```

---

### Phase 6 — Multi-tenancy / RBAC on who can read logs

```bash
oc get clusterrole | grep -i cluster-logging
oc get clusterrolebinding | grep -i cluster-logging-view
```
Loki on OCP is tenant-partitioned by default into `application`, `infrastructure`, and `audit` — worth knowing who's bound to `cluster-logging-application-view` vs the infra/audit equivalents, especially under PCI-DSS since audit logs should have a much tighter read list than application logs.

---

### Phase 7 (bonus) — Where this connects to metrics/alerting

```bash
oc get pods -n openshift-monitoring | grep -iE "prometheus|alertmanager|thanos"
oc get prometheusrule -n openshift-logging          # Loki-based alerting rules, if configured
```

